ermanic languages have front rounded vowels except for English. Dutch, German, Swedish, Finnish, and Norwegian all have front rounded vowels so it is odd that English would be one of the only German-based languages which is missing this linguistic feature. English does have rounded vowels, but none of them are produced at the front of the mouth. WALS explains that the front rounded vowels tend to appear in languages with larger vowel quality inventory, but English is also categorized by WALS as having a large vowel quality inventory which makes its lack of front rounded vowels even stranger. Odder still is the fact that French is a Romance or Latin-based language, and seems to be one of the only of its language family that DOES have the front rounded vowel linguistic feature. WALS explains this as the back rounded vowels in Latin being moved forward in French so that they are now front rounded, the example given being the rounded vowel in Latin 'tu' becoming the French 'vous'.%0a%3c %0a%3c Does the additional vowel inventory provided by these front rounded vowels allow for a more complex language, and does this greater degree of complexity make French more efficient or less likely to be misunderstood/misinterpreted?%0a%3c %0a%3c SOURCES:%0a%3c https://wals.info/chapter/11%0a%3c https://wals.info/feature/11A#2/22.6/152.8%0a%3c https://phoible.org/inventories/view/162%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Expansions:%0a%3c [[#expansions]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#expansionsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%3c %0a%3c (:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:else:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Comments%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c (:section: :)%0a%3c (:Category: TypologyOfPhoneticContrasts:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
